<section class="expert-philosophy">
    <h2>Core Philosophy & Approach</h2>

    <blockquote class="featured-quote">
        "Genetics has revealed that not all lipoproteins are created equal in terms of cardiovascular risk. HDL raising hasn't panned out, but apoB-containing particles consistently predict risk. Genetics also points to Lp(a) as an undertreated causal risk factor."
    </blockquote>

    <p>Dr. Daniel Rader is one of the world's leading researchers in cardiovascular genetics. His work uses genetic approaches to identify causal pathways in heart disease, helping distinguish risk markers from actual causes.</p>

    <p>His research has been particularly important in understanding why HDL-raising drugs failed (despite HDL being associated with lower risk) and in identifying Lipoprotein(a) as an important genetic risk factor that represents a new therapeutic target.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Central Arguments</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Genetics reveals causality</strong> - Genetic studies can distinguish risk markers from actual causes</li>
            <li><strong>HDL complexity</strong> - HDL levels predict risk, but raising HDL doesn't necessarily reduce it</li>
            <li><strong>Lp(a) matters</strong> - Lipoprotein(a) is a genetically-determined causal risk factor needing new treatments</li>
            <li><strong>ApoB is key</strong> - ApoB-containing particles consistently drive cardiovascular risk</li>
            <li><strong>Precision medicine</strong> - Genetic information can guide personalized cardiovascular care</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

